The 30-Minute Demo
The quickstart is genuinely good. If you follow the Model Context Protocol docs for TypeScript, you’ll have a server running on stdio in under thirty min
utes. Define a tool, export it, connect it to Claude Desktop. Magic.
import { Server } from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/index.js'const server = new Server({
name: 'my-server',
version: '1.0.0',
}, {
capabilities: { tools: {} }
})server.setRequestHandler(ListToolsRequestSchema, async () => ({
tools: [{
name: 'search_docs',
description: 'Search internal documentation',
inputSchema: {
type: 'object',
properties: {
query: { type: 'string' }
}
}
}]
}))This works. In 30 minutes, you’ve built an MCP server. Congratulations.
What Broke First: Timeouts
The demo server works great when everything is local and fast. But the first time I pointed it at a remote API that took 15 seconds to respond, Claude Desktop showed me an error: “Tool call timed out.”
There’s no built-in timeout handling in the basic SDK setup. The host has its own timeout, and if your tool doesn’t respond in time, it just fails. No retry. No warning. Just a red error in the chat.
The fix was to add proper timeout management to my tool handlers:
server.setRequestHandler(CallToolRequestSchema, async (request) => {
const { name, arguments: args } = request.params const timeout = 30000
const controller = new AbortController()
const timer = setTimeout(() => controller.abort(), timeout)
try {
const result = await executeWithTimeout(name, args, controller.signal)
return { content: [{ type: 'text', text: JSON.stringify(result) }] }
} catch (error) {
if (controller.signal.aborted) {
return { content: [{ type: 'text', text: 'Tool execution timed out' }], isError: true }
}
throw error
} finally {
clearTimeout(timer)
}
})
What Broke Second: Silent Crashes
My server worked for exactly three tool calls. Then it stopped. No error in the console. No crash log. Claude Desktop just said the server disconnected.
The issue? An unhandled promise rejection in one of my tool handlers. The MCP SDK catches errors at the protocol level, but if your async function throws before it reaches the request handler — say, in a validation step — the server process dies without a word.
The lesson: wrap every tool handler with a try-catch at the outermost layer, and log to stderr (not stdout, which MCP uses for its protocol messages).
process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason) => {
console.error('[FATAL] Unhandled rejection:', reason)
})What Broke Third: Tool Discovery
I registered five tools. The host only saw three. I spent an hour debugging before I realized: one of the tools had a name that started with a number, and the JSON Schema validator silently dropped it.
MCP uses JSON Schema for tool definitions. If a tool’s inputSchema is invalid, the entire tool registration silently fails. No error. No warning. The tool just doesn’t appear.
Test your schema separately:
function validateToolSchema(tool) {
try {
AJV.validate(tool.inputSchema)
return true
} catch {
return false
}
}What Still Bugs Me
I still haven’t figured out the right approach for streaming progress updates. The MCP spec supports notifications/progress, but each host implements it differently. Claude Desktop handles it one way, VS Code’s MCP integration another.
Also, stdio transport is fine for development, but it’s terrible for production. Every time the host restarts, your server restarts. Every crash loses state. I’m migrating to Streamable HTTP, but that opens a whole new can of worms with authentication and CORS.
The Bottom Line
MCP is genuinely useful. The spec is clean, the SDK works, and having a standardized protocol for AI tools is a big deal. But the tutorials make it look too easy. The hard parts — error handling, timeout management, schema validation, transport decisions — are where the real engineering lives.
Build your demo in 30 minutes. Just don’t ship it until you’ve fixed the things the tutorials skip.
